   }\\n    }\\n    remoteTree, remoteErr := strategy.GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    if remoteErr != nil {\\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"metadata branch not available: %w\\\", remoteErr)\\n    }\\n    return remoteTree, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**What existed in the same file before this diff (the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`):**\\n\\nThis is exactly the logic that was extracted. The deletion of `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` and the creation of `getMetadataTree()` is a direct refactor — the same three steps existed inline in the removed function. The extraction is correct and produces less total code than before. No duplication concern here.\\n\\n**`checkRemoteMetadata` (resume.go:397-425) — different pattern, not a reuse opportunity:**\\n\\nThis function uses `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` and `FetchMetadataBranch` but in a different way: it first checks the remote tree to confirm the checkpoint actually exists there before fetching, and returns early with a user-facing error message if it does not. The semantics are different (confirm-then-fetch vs best-effort fetch-then-fallback), so merging them into `getMetadataTree()` would not be appropriate.\\n\\n**`resumeSession` (resume.go:437-440) — does not use `getMetadataTree()`:**\\n\\n```go\\nmetadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\nif err != nil {\\n    return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get metadata branch: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis call site is reached only after `checkRemoteMetadata` has already fetched the branch and returned successfully (the caller returns before reaching `resumeSession` if the local branch is absent). So the local-only lookup is correct in context: by the time `resumeSession` runs, the metadata branch is guaranteed to be present locally. This is not a missed reuse opportunity.\\n\\n**Verdict: no issue.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### `resolveLatestCheckpoint()` — \\\"get latest checkpoint\\\" logic\\n\\n**The new function (resume.go:188-201):**\\n\\n```go\\nfunc resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo *git.Repository, checkpointIDs []id.CheckpointID) (id.CheckpointID, error) {\\n    metadataTree, err := getMetadataTree(repo)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, err\\n    }\\n    sorted := collectCheckpointsByAge(metadataTree, checkpointIDs)\\n    if len(sorted) == 0 {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")\\n    }\\n    return sorted[len(sorted)-1].CheckpointID, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Does similar \\\"get the latest\\\" logic exist elsewhere?** Searching the codebase for `GetMetadataBranchTree` usage at:\\n\\n- `strategy/session.go:187` — reads a single checkpoint tree, does not sort or compare multiple, no overlap.\\n- `strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go:163` — best-effort read for session prompts, no sorting, no overlap.\\n- `explain.go:927` — iterates commits and reads their checkpoint metadata one at a time via `ReadCheckpointMetadata`, does not compare `CreatedAt` across a set of IDs, no overlap.\\n\\nNo existing \\\"sort by CreatedAt and return last\\\" pattern exists elsewhere in the codebase. `collectCheckpointsByAge` itself was already present before this diff. `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a thin wrapper that adds the `getMetadataTree` step and the tail-element extraction — it is not duplicating any other utility.\\n\\n**Verdict: no issue.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:212]** `getMetadataTree` calls `FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background())` instead of threading through the `ctx` passed to its call sites. This drops any cancellation or deadline set by the caller (for example, a CLI timeout). The function signature only takes `*git.Repository`, so `ctx` is unavailable inside it without a signature change.\\n\\nThere are two practical approaches:\\n\\nOption A — add `ctx` parameter:\\n```go\\nfunc getMetadataTree(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n```\\nand pass `ctx` through from `resolveLatestCheckpoint`, which would in turn receive it from `resumeFromCurrentBranch`. This is the cleanest fix.\\n\\nOption B — leave `context.Background()` and add a comment explaining the limitation. Acceptable only if the fetch is intentionally fire-and-forget, but given that the rest of `resume.go` passes `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch` (line 417), this is inconsistent.\\n\\nThe deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` passed the real `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch`. This is a regression introduced by the refactor. Notably, this exact issue does not appear in `checkRemoteMetadata` (line 417) which correctly receives `ctx` and passes it through.\\n\\n**Fix:** Add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to `getMetadataTree` and update the two call sites (`resolveLatestCheckpoint` and any direct callers).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:196]** `resolveLatestCheckpoint` calls `getMetadataTree` which may perform a network fetch. At the call site (resume.go:160), if `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails, the fallback is `result.checkpointIDs[len-1]` (the last trailer), which is the same checkpoint that `resumeFromCurrentBranch` would have used for the single-checkpoint path anyway. This means the fetch in `getMetadataTree` is speculative: it is attempted even in contexts where a simpler fallback is acceptable. This is not a bug, but a `logging.Debug` call on the `resolveLatestCheckpoint` error path (currently silently ignored at line 162) would improve diagnosability when the fetch fails.\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:163]** The fallback comment says \\\"use last trailer\\\" — in practice this means the most recently added trailer, which by the squash-merge ordering tested in the integration test corresponds to the most recently created checkpoint. This happens to be correct, but it is order-dependent on how `git` serialises trailers during squash merge. A comment linking to the ordering assumption (or the test that validates it) would