56-168]** The initial assignment `checkpointID := result.checkpointIDs[0]` is immediately a dead write when `len(result.checkpointIDs) > 1`. The value assigned on line 156 is unconditionally overwritten on line 168 (`checkpointID = latest`). This makes the reader wonder whether `checkpointIDs[0]` has any semantic significance for the single-checkpoint case, and why the initial value is not `result.checkpointIDs[len-1]` or some other element for the multi-checkpoint fallback path.\\n\\n   A cleaner structure would remove the ambiguity entirely:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   var checkpointID id.CheckpointID\\n   if len(result.checkpointIDs) == 1 {\\n       checkpointID = result.checkpointIDs[0]\\n   } else {\\n       // Multiple checkpoints (squash merge): resolve latest and resume from it\\n       latest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\n       if err != nil {\\n           // Fallback: use last trailer\\n           latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n       }\\n       skipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit in this branch, resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs), skipped)\\n       checkpointID = latest\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This makes each branch explicit: the single-checkpoint case assigns `[0]`, and the multi-checkpoint case assigns `latest`. No dead write, no misleading initial value.\\n\\n2. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:212]** `getMetadataTree` calls `FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background())` instead of threading the caller's context through. This means:\\n   - Cancellation of the parent context (e.g., user pressing Ctrl-C) does not cancel an in-progress fetch during checkpoint resolution.\\n   - Timeouts set on the incoming context are silently ignored.\\n\\n   This is a deviation from the established pattern in the codebase: `checkRemoteMetadata` (line 417) and `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` (the removed function, which passed `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch`) both used the caller's context correctly.\\n\\n   `getMetadataTree` does not accept a context parameter, which is the root cause. Adding `ctx context.Context` as a first parameter and propagating it to `FetchMetadataBranch(ctx)` fixes this.\\n\\n   This is particularly worth fixing because `getMetadataTree` is called from `resolveLatestCheckpoint`, which is called from within the hot path of `resumeFromCurrentBranch`. A slow or stalled network fetch during checkpoint resolution will not respect any deadline or cancellation.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n1. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:161-163]** The fallback logic uses `result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]` (the last trailer) when `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails. The comment says \\\"use last trailer\\\". This is reasonable if trailers appear in chronological order, but the comment in the surrounding test (`TestFindCheckpointInHistory_MultipleCheckpoints`) documents that git CLI squash merges write trailers in reverse chronological order (newest first, so `[0]` would be newest). If that ordering assumption holds, `[0]` would be a better fallback than `[len-1]`.\\n\\n   However, since the fallback only fires when metadata cannot be read at all (no local branch, fetch failed, no remote), the ordering assumption cannot be verified at runtime anyway. The choice between first and last is a coin flip in the fallback case. Adding a comment acknowledging this ambiguity would help future readers:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   // Fallback: use last trailer. Trailer order is not guaranteed,\\n   // but this is a best-effort choice when metadata is unavailable.\\n   latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:164-167]** The informational message is printed even when `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails and the fallback is used. In the fallback case, the message says \\\"resuming from the latest\\\" but the resolution was actually a guess (last trailer, not verified by metadata). Consider printing a different message on the error path to be accurate:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   latest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\n   if err != nil {\\n       latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit, could not determine order (resuming from last trailer)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs))\\n   } else {\\n       skipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit in this branch, resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs), skipped)\\n   }\\n   checkpointID = latest\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:191-225]** `resolveLatestCheckpoint` and `getMetadataTree` are only called from the multi-checkpoint branch of `resumeFromCurrentBranch`. Immediately below (lines 171-184), the single-checkpoint path calls `strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree` and `checkRemoteMetadata` directly, using a separate (and partially overlapping) remote-fallback logic. This means the remote fallback logic is implemented twice: once in `getMetadataTree` (for the multi-checkpoint path) and once inline in `resumeFromCurrentBranch` (for the single-checkpoint path). The duplication is not a correctness issue for this diff, but it is worth noting as a maintenance burden. A follow-up to unify the two fallback paths (possibly by having both cases go through `getMetadataTree`) would reduce the surface area.\\n\\n4. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume_test.go:443-481]** `TestResolveLatestCheckpoint` does not test the error path (when the metadata branch has no entries for any of the provided checkpoint IDs). A test that calls `resolveLatestCheckpoint` with IDs that don't exist in the metadata tree would verify that the `errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")` error is returned correctly, and that callers receive a usable error to fall back on.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- Removing `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` and `deduplicateSessions` is a clear simplification. The old approach required restoring all sessions and deduplicating by `SessionID`, which was ~80 lines. The new approach is ~10 lines. The feature change (resume only the latest, not all) is a legitimate product decision and the code change correctly implements it.\\n\\n- `getMetadataTree` cleanly encapsulates the three-step fallback (local branch → fetch → remote tree). The step ordering is correct: try cheapest operation first, escalate to network calls only as needed. The comments on each step are clear.\\n\\n- `collectCheckpointsByAge` is unchanged and continues to be correct. Sorting ascending by `CreatedAt` and returning `sorted[len-1]` (the newest) is a correct and readable implementation of \\\"find the latest.\\\"\\n\\n- The integration test update (`TestResume_SquashMergeMultipleCheckpoints`) correctly narrows the assertion: the old test asserted that both session IDs appeared in output, the new test asserts only `session2.ID` appears. The test accurately reflects the new single-session contract.\\n\\n- `TestResolveLatestCheckpoint` tests both orderings (reverse-chronological and chronological) of the input slice, which is the exact scenario that motivated this change. This is good coverage of the core invariant.\\n\\n- Deleting `TestDeduplicateSessions` along with `deduplicateSessions` is correct housekeeping. Tests for deleted code should not linger.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe change is a clean simplification with correct logic and appropriate test updates. Two issues are worth addressing before merge:\\n\\n1. **Important**: The dead initial write of `checkpointID` creates reader confusion — restructure to make single vs. multi-checkpoint paths explicit branches.\\n2. **Important**: `getMetadataTree` drops the caller's context by using `context.Background()`, breaking cancellation and timeout propagation for the fetch step.\\n\\nThe suggestions are low-priority polish (fallback message accuracy, test coverage of the error path, commentary on the known ordering ambiguity).\\n\\n**Overall verdict: APPROVE** — the logic is correct and the simplification is a net improvement. The two Important items are worth fixing but are not blockers for correctness.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback: ~30 minutes**\\n- Restructure `checkpointID` assignment: ~10 minutes\\n- Add `ctx` parameter to `getMetadataTree`: ~10 minutes\\n- Optional: message accuracy in fallback case, error path test: ~10 minutes\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":151,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":60606,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":151},\"output_tokens\":18,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYhtuW1ssu9ZWJCkhbP7g\",\"uuid\":\"1fbb6810-4b6f-4f8a-9534-627c73795ee9\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a89c0a9858f95dd0e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Cefnh1vBkZAEVuFxXh1GyF\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01TaBUrhmiHzHp5MBwgav4pT\",\"uuid\":\"a3a110cd-3b84-43d9-bf92-3805ae713f9e\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:39:32.680Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"a3a110cd-3b84-43d9-bf92-3805ae713f9e\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"<tool_use_error>File has not been read yet. Read it first before writing to it.</to