→ fetch → remote-tree fallback\\n    21→\\n    22→**The new function (resume.go:205-225):**\\n    23→\\n    24→```go\\n    25→func getMetadataTree(repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n    26→    metadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    27→    if err == nil {\\n    28→        return metadataTree, nil\\n    29→    }\\n    30→    if fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background()); fetchErr == nil {\\n    31→        metadataTree, err = strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    32→        if err == nil {\\n    33→            return metadataTree, nil\\n    34→        }\\n    35→    }\\n    36→    remoteTree, remoteErr := strategy.GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    37→    if remoteErr != nil {\\n    38→        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"metadata branch not available: %w\\\", remoteErr)\\n    39→    }\\n    40→    return remoteTree, nil\\n    41→}\\n    42→```\\n    43→\\n    44→**What existed in the same file before this diff (the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`):**\\n    45→\\n    46→This is exactly the logic that was extracted. The deletion of `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` and the creation of `getMetadataTree()` is a direct refactor — the same three steps existed inline in the removed function. The extraction is correct and produces less total code than before. No duplication concern here.\\n    47→\\n    48→**`checkRemoteMetadata` (resume.go:397-425) — different pattern, not a reuse opportunity:**\\n    49→\\n    50→This function uses `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` and `FetchMetadataBranch` but in a different way: it first checks the remote tree to confirm the checkpoint actually exists there before fetching, and returns early with a user-facing error message if it does not. The semantics are different (confirm-then-fetch vs best-effort fetch-then-fallback), so merging them into `getMetadataTree()` would not be appropriate.\\n    51→\\n    52→**`resumeSession` (resume.go:437-440) — does not use `getMetadataTree()`:**\\n    53→\\n    54→```go\\n    55→metadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    56→if err != nil {\\n    57→    return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get metadata branch: %w\\\", err)\\n    58→}\\n    59→```\\n    60→\\n    61→This call site is reached only after `checkRemoteMetadata` has already fetched the branch and returned successfully (the caller returns before reaching `resumeSession` if the local branch is absent). So the local-only lookup is correct in context: by the time `resumeSession` runs, the metadata branch is guaranteed to be present locally. This is not a missed reuse opportunity.\\n    62→\\n    63→**Verdict: no issue.**\\n    64→\\n    65→---\\n    66→\\n    67→### `resolveLatestCheckpoint()` — \\\"get latest checkpoint\\\" logic\\n    68→\\n    69→**The new function (resume.go:188-201):**\\n    70→\\n    71→```go\\n    72→func resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo *git.Repository, checkpointIDs []id.CheckpointID) (id.CheckpointID, error) {\\n    73→    metadataTree, err := getMetadataTree(repo)\\n    74→    if err != nil {\\n    75→        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, err\\n    76→    }\\n    77→    sorted := collectCheckpointsByAge(metadataTree, checkpointIDs)\\n    78→    if len(sorted) == 0 {\\n    79→        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")\\n    80→    }\\n    81→    return sorted[len(sorted)-1].CheckpointID, nil\\n    82→}\\n    83→```\\n    84→\\n    85→**Does similar \\\"get the latest\\\" logic exist elsewhere?** Searching the codebase for `GetMetadataBranchTree` usage at:\\n    86→\\n    87→- `strategy/session.go:187` — reads a single checkpoint tree, does not sort or compare multiple, no overlap.\\n    88→- `strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go:163` — best-effort read for session prompts, no sorting, no overlap.\\n    89→- `explain.go:927` — iterates commits and reads their checkpoint metadata one at a time via `ReadCheckpointMetadata`, does not compare `CreatedAt` across a set of IDs, no overlap.\\n    90→\\n    91→No existing \\\"sort by CreatedAt and return last\\\" pattern exists elsewhere in the codebase. `collectCheckpointsByAge` itself was already present before this diff. `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a thin wrapper that adds the `getMetadataTree` step and the tail-element extraction — it is not duplicating any other utility.\\n    92→\\n    93→**Verdict: no issue.**\\n    94→\\n    95→---\\n    96→\\n    97→### Critical (Must Fix)\\n    98→\\n    99→**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:212]** `getMetadataTree` calls `FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background())` instead of threading through the `ctx` passed to its call sites. This drops any cancellation or deadline set by the caller (for example, a CLI timeout). The function signature only takes `*git.Repository`, so `ctx` is unavailable inside it without a signature change.\\n   100→\\n   101→There are two practical approaches:\\n   102→\\n   103→Option A — add `ctx` parameter:\\n   104→```go\\n   105→func getMetadataTree(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n   106→```\\n   107→and pass `ctx` through from `resolveLatestCheckpoint`, which would in turn receive it from `resumeFromCurrentBranch`. This is the cleanest fix.\\n   108→\\n   109→Option B — leave `context.Background()` and add a comment explaining the limitation. Acceptable only if the fetch is intentionally fire-and-forget, but given that the rest of `resume.go` passes `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch` (line 417), this is inconsistent.\\n   110→\\n   111→The deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` passed the real `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch`. This is a regression introduced by the refactor. Notably, this exact issue does not appear in `checkRemoteMetadata` (line 417) which correctly receives `ctx` and passes it through.\\n   112→\\n   113→**Fix:** Add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to `getMetadataTree` and update the two call sites (`resolveLatestCheckpoint` and any direct callers).\\n   114→\\n   115→---\\n   116→\\n   117→### Suggestions (Consider)\\n   118→\\n   119→**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:196]** `resolveLatestCheckpoint` calls `getMetadataTree` which may perform a network fetch. At the call site (resume.go:160), if `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails, the fallback is `result.checkpointIDs[len-1]` (the last trailer), which is the same checkpoint that `resumeFromCurrentBranch` would have used for the single-checkpoint path anyway. This means the fetch in `getMetadataTree` is speculative: it is attempted even in contexts where a simpler fallback is acceptable. This is not a bug, but a `logging.Debug` call on the `resolveLatestCheckpoint` error path (currently silently ignored at line 162) would improve diagnosability when the fetch fails.\\n   120→\\n   121→**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:163]** The fallback comment says \\\"use last trailer\\\" — in practice this means the most recently added trailer, which by the squash-merge ordering tested in the integration test corresponds to the most recently created checkpoint. This happens to be correct, but it is order-dependent on how `git` serialises trailers during squash merge. A comment linking to the ordering assumption (or the test that validates it) would make the fallback easier to audit.\\n   122→\\n   123→---\\n   124→\\n   125→### Praise\\n   126→\\n   127→- Extracting `getMetadataTree()` correctly eliminates the duplication of the three-step fallback pattern that previously existed inline in `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`. The pre-diff code had that logic in one place; the post-diff code also has it in one place, just named.\\n   128→- `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a clean, single-responsibility wrapper. The two-call test in `resume_test.go` (reverse-order and chronological-order) directly validates the invariant.\\n   129→- Removing `deduplicateSessions` and `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` reduces the file by ~100 lines without losing correctness — the squash-merge case is now handled by returning the single latest checkpoint rather than restoring all of them, which is a simpler and more predictable user experience.\\n   130→- The integration test update (`TestResume_SquashMergeMultipleCheckpoints`) correctly reflects the new behaviour: it now asserts on the `\\\"older checkpoints skipped\\\"` message and session2 ID rather than \\\"Restored 2 sessions\\\" and both session IDs.\\n   131→\\n   132→---\\n   133→\\n   134→## Summary\\n   135→\\n   136→**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n   137→\\n   138→One issue must be addressed before merge:\\n   139→\\n   140→- **[resume.go:212]** `context.Background()` in `getMetadataTree` is a regression from the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`, which passed the real `ctx`. Add `ctx context.Context` to `getMetadataTree`'s signature.\\n   141→\\n   142→No code-reuse problems were found. `getMetadataTree` is a correct extraction of logic that was previously duplicated between the call sites. `resolveLatestCheckpoint` does not duplicate any existing utility.\\n   143→\\n   144→**Estimated effort to address: ~15 minutes** (signature change + two call sites).\\n   145→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"62df8924-c887-47de-91d9-8ed7381fa384\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:39:37.659Z\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a89c0a9858f95dd0e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Cefnh1vBkZAEVuFxXh1GyF\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01TaBUrhmiHzHp5MBwgav4pT\",\"uuid\":\"c67b11b9-b679-4049-89d7-e6c3703fa96a\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:39:37.660Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c67b11b9-b679-4049-89d7-e6c3703fa96a\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:39:58.867Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01Qv9XNtNyLeQ5ee9uthXpzX\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01PT9cb2qFhNtT8cPtGMZfHu\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/single-commit-per-checkpoint/review-04.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 04\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-04\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis review covers the single commit on the branch (`d90158f2`):\\n\\\"use only the latest checkpoint for entire resume on squashed commits\\\"\\n\\nThe diff is scoped to `cmd/entire/cli/resume.go` and its tests. This is a focused\\nefficiency/behaviour change: instead of restoring ALL sessions from a squash commit's\\nmultiple checkpoint trailers, `resume` now resolves the single latest one and resumes\\nonly that.\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nItems from review-03 are not addressed by this commit (different concern). They remain\\nopen on the branch and are tracked separately. This review evaluates only the new code\\nintroduced by this commit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n**1. [resume.go:212] `FetchMetadataBranch` called with `context.Background()` — drops\\ncancellation and timeout from the caller**\\n\\n```go\\nif fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background()); fetchErr == nil {\\n```\\n\\n`FetchMetadataBranch` wraps the fetch in its own 2-minute timeout (line 365 of\\n`git_operations.go`), so the operation is not truly unbounded. However, using\\n`context.Background()` instead of the caller-provided `ctx` means that if the user sends\\nSIGINT / Ctrl-C while the CLI is running, the fetch will not be cancelled. The user will\\nhave to wait up to 2 minutes for the timeout to fire before the process exits. Every\\nother call to `FetchMetadataBranch` in the file (lines 97, 417) correctly threads `ctx`\\nthrough.\\n\\n`getMetadataTree` does not receive `ctx` because it takes only `*git.Repository`. That is\\nthe root cause. The fix is to add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to\\n`getMetadataTree` and `resolveLatestCheckpoint` and thread it through.\\n\\n```go\\n// Before\\nfunc getMetadataTree(repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n\\n// After\\nfunc getMetadataTree(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n    ...\\n    if fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(ctx); fetchErr == nil {\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n**2. [resume.go:191-200 vs 172-185] `GetMetadataBranchTree` is called twice in the\\nmulti-checkpoint path — once inside `resolveLatestCheckpoint` → `getMetadataTree`, and\\nagain in `resumeFromCurrentBranch` at line 172**\\n\\nThe call sequence when `len(result.checkpointIDs) > 1`:\\n\\n```\\nresolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, ...)\\n  └── getMetadataTree(repo)\\n        └── strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)   ← tree fetch #1\\n              (possibly FetchMetadataBranch + GetMetadataBranchTree if local not found)\\n\\n// back in resumeFromCurrentBranch:\\nstrategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)               ← tree fetch #2\\n```\\n\\n`GetMetadataBranchTree` resolves a branch reference, reads its commit object, and\\nresolves the tree object via go-git's object store. In the local case, go-git caches\\nobjects in memory after the first read, so the second call is cheap. However:\\n\\n- It is **not a no-op**: the reference must still be resolved via `repo.Reference()` and\\n  `repo.CommitObject()` on each call. This involves filesystem reads from `.git/`.\\n- More importantly, in the **remote-fetch path** (local branch absent), `getMetadataTree`\\n  may call `FetchMetadataBranch` and then re-resolve the tree. The subsequent call at\\n  line 172 will succeed (the branch now exists locally) but is still a redundant\\n  round-trip through reference resolution.\\n- If the tree is fetched via `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` inside `getMetadataTree` (the\\n  third fallback), `resolveLatestCheckpoint` sorts using that remote tree — but then\\n  `resumeFromCurrentBranch` calls `GetMetadataBranchTree` (local), which still fails,\\n  and falls through to `checkRemoteMetadata`. `checkRemoteMetadata` then calls\\n  `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` **a third time** and `ReadCheckpointMetadata` again on\\n  the same tree. That is three tree resolutions and two metadata reads for one checkpoint\\n  in the remote-only path.\\n\\nThe clean fix is to return the resolved tree from `resolveLatestCheckpoint` (or\\n`getMetadataTree`) and pass it to the subsequent `ReadCheckpointMetadata` call:\\n\\n```go\\n// resolveLatestCheckpoint returns both the chosen ID and the tree it used\\nfunc resolveLatestCheckpoint(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository, ids []id.CheckpointID) (id.CheckpointID, *object.Tree, error) {\\n    tree, err := getMetadataTree(ctx, repo)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, nil, err\\n    }\\n    sorted := collectCheckpointsByAge(tree, ids)\\n    if len(sorted) == 0 {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, nil, errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")\\n    }\\n    return sorted[len(sorted)-1].CheckpointID, tree, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThen in `resumeFromCurrentBranch`, reuse the returned tree instead of calling\\n`GetMetadataBranchTree` again.\\n\\n**3. [resume.go:231-243] `collectCheckpointsByAge` reads FULL metadata for every\\ncheckpoint just to compare timestamps — O(N) metadata reads when only `CreatedAt` is\\nneeded**\\n\\n`ReadCheckpointMetadata` (common.go:363) does the following for each checkpoint in the\\nnew format:\\n1. Reads and JSON-parses `metadata.json` (the `CheckpointSummary`)\\n2. For each session in the summary, reads and JSON-parses the per-session `metadata.json`\\n   from its numbered subdirectory\\n\\nFor a squash commit with N checkpoint trailers, this is O(N × S) file reads and JSON\\nparses, where S is the average session count per checkpoint. All of this data is thrown\\naway except `CreatedAt`.\\n\\nThe `CheckpointSummary` struct does not include `CreatedAt` directly, but\\n`CommittedMetadata` (the per-session file) does. Since only the first session's\\n`CreatedAt` is used (line 400 of `ReadCheckpointMetadata`: \\\"Use first session for Agent,\\nSessionID, CreatedAt\\\"), a lighter approach would be to read only the root `metadata.json`\\nand extract the first session path, then read only that session's `metadata.json`.\\n\\nHowever, in the current metadata format, `CheckpointSummary` itself does not contain\\n`CreatedAt`. The per-session metadata must be read for the timestamp. There are two\\npractical mitigations:\\n\\na. **Read the first session's metadata only** (not all sessions) just for the timestamp\\n   comparison in `collectCheckpointsByAge`. The full read can still happen later for the\\n   chosen checkpoint. This reduces the cost from O(N × S) to O(N × 1).\\n\\nb. **Add `CreatedAt` to `CheckpointSummary`** so the summary read alone suffices. This\\n   is a deeper structural change but would benefit any future caller that needs only\\n   summary info.\\n\\nIn practice, squash commits rarely accumulate more than a handful of checkpoint trailers\\n(typically 2–5), so the performance impact is bounded. This is an improvement to make,\\nnot a blocker, but it should not be ignored as checkpoints accumulate on long-lived\\nbranches.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**4. [resume.go:163-169] The fallback path in `resolveLatestCheckpoint` uses the last\\ntrailer rather than trying per-checkpoint timestamps**\\n\\n```go\\nlatest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\nif err != nil {\\n    // Fallback: use last trailer\\n    latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe fallback assumption (last trailer = latest checkpoint) is reasonable — git commit\\nmessages preserve insertion order and the most recent checkpoint is appended last — but\\nit is undocumented. A brief comment would clarify the intent:\\n\\n```go\\n// Fallback: trailers appear in insertion order, so the last one is the most recent.\\nlatest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n```\\n\\n**5. [resume.go:163-169] Silent fallback on `resolveLatestCheckpoint` error may surprise\\nusers**\\n\\nIf `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails (e.g., metadata branch is unavailable), the code\\nsilently falls back to the last trailer and continues. The user sees the \\\"older\\ncheckpoints skipped\\\" message without any indication that the \\\"latest\\\" was determined by\\ntrailer order rather than actual metadata. Consider a debug log or, if metadata is\\nunavailable, outputting a note like \\\"metadata unavailable, assuming last checkpoint is\\nlatest\\\". At minimum, the debug logging path that was removed from the old\\n`resumeMultipleCheckpoints` (which logged \\\"metadata branch not available locally, trying\\nremote\\\") is no longer reachable.\\n\\n**6. [resume.go:165-167] Skipped count includes the latest itself**\\n\\n```go\\nskipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\nfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit in this branch, resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\",\\n    len(result.checkpointIDs), skipped)\\n```\\n\\nThis arithmetic is correct (N checkpoints, N-1 skipped). However, the message says\\n\\\"Found N checkpoints\\\" even when `resolveLatestCheckpoint` failed and the fallback was\\nused. In that case, the \\\"latest\\\" was chosen by trailer position, not by timestamp — the\\nmessage should not imply it was determined from metadata.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- The core behaviour change is correct and well-motivated. Restoring all sessions from a\\n  squash commit is surprising UX: the user asked to resume one session, not N. Selecting\\n  the latest and skipping older ones is the right default.\\n\\n- The deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` function and `deduplicateSessions` function\\n  remove ~115 lines of bespoke complexity. The replacement (`resolveLatestCheckpoint` +\\n  `collectCheckpointsByAge` reuse) is cleaner and more direct.\\n\\n- `collectCheckpointsByAge` is properly shared between the resolve path and (previously)\\n  the multi-restore path — good reuse of an already-tested helper.\\n\\n- The test update in `integration_test/resume_test.go` correctly documents the new\\n  contract: one session restored, skipped count shown, session ID present.\\n\\n- The fallback to `result.checkpointIDs[len-1]` ensures the feature degrades gracefully\\n  when the metadata branch is unreachable, rather than erroring out.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\n**Key concerns:**\\n\\n1. `context.Background()` in `getMetadataTree` prevents signal cancellation — easy fix,\\n   just add `ctx` parameter.\\n\\n2. Double (and in the remote fallback path, triple) call to `GetMetadataBranchTree` plus\\n   redundant `ReadCheckpointMetadata` call after `resolveLatestCheckpoint`. Return the\\n   tree from `resolveLatestCheckpoint` and reuse it.\\n\\n3. `collectCheckpointsByAge` reads full per-session metadata for every checkpoint ID just\\n   to compare `CreatedAt` timestamps. For the common case of a small N this is fine, but\\n   reading only the first session's metadata per checkpoint would halve the I/O.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback: ~1 hour**\\n- Context threading (items 1 + 2): ~30 minutes\\n- Partial metadata read for timestamp comparison (item 3): ~20 minutes\\n- Comments / log messages (items 4–6): ~10 minutes\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":3642,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":49140,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":3642},\"output_tokens\":2,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYht