ID\":\"agent_msg_01Cefnh1vBkZAEVuFxXh1GyF\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_018RrVSvpx8zGSKYfkz6BShF\",\"uuid\":\"40881f98-0edd-4100-9d4f-6a91816ba501\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:40:01.936Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"40881f98-0edd-4100-9d4f-6a91816ba501\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:41:01.182Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-sonnet-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01P4Weg9jvbWeUT7ahGMAtTa\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01LLW8yUCHFB4tatEE5eWksE\",\"name\":\"Edit\",\"input\":{\"replace_all\":false,\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/single-commit-per-checkpoint/review-04.md\",\"old_string\":\"# Review 04\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-04\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: REQUEST CHANGES (one issue)\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis review covers only `cmd/entire/cli/resume.go`, `cmd/entire/cli/resume_test.go`, and `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/resume_test.go` and focuses exclusively on **code reuse**: does any new code duplicate logic that already exists elsewhere?\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nNot applicable — this is a scoped incremental review of the resume changes only.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Code Reuse Findings\\n\\n### `getMetadataTree()` — three-step local → fetch → remote-tree fallback\\n\\n**The new function (resume.go:205-225):**\\n\\n```go\\nfunc getMetadataTree(repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n    metadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    if err == nil {\\n        return metadataTree, nil\\n    }\\n    if fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background()); fetchErr == nil {\\n        metadataTree, err = strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n        if err == nil {\\n            return metadataTree, nil\\n        }\\n    }\\n    remoteTree, remoteErr := strategy.GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\n    if remoteErr != nil {\\n        return nil, fmt.Errorf(\\\"metadata branch not available: %w\\\", remoteErr)\\n    }\\n    return remoteTree, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**What existed in the same file before this diff (the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`):**\\n\\nThis is exactly the logic that was extracted. The deletion of `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` and the creation of `getMetadataTree()` is a direct refactor — the same three steps existed inline in the removed function. The extraction is correct and produces less total code than before. No duplication concern here.\\n\\n**`checkRemoteMetadata` (resume.go:397-425) — different pattern, not a reuse opportunity:**\\n\\nThis function uses `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` and `FetchMetadataBranch` but in a different way: it first checks the remote tree to confirm the checkpoint actually exists there before fetching, and returns early with a user-facing error message if it does not. The semantics are different (confirm-then-fetch vs best-effort fetch-then-fallback), so merging them into `getMetadataTree()` would not be appropriate.\\n\\n**`resumeSession` (resume.go:437-440) — does not use `getMetadataTree()`:**\\n\\n```go\\nmetadataTree, err := strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)\\nif err != nil {\\n    return fmt.Errorf(\\\"failed to get metadata branch: %w\\\", err)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThis call site is reached only after `checkRemoteMetadata` has already fetched the branch and returned successfully (the caller returns before reaching `resumeSession` if the local branch is absent). So the local-only lookup is correct in context: by the time `resumeSession` runs, the metadata branch is guaranteed to be present locally. This is not a missed reuse opportunity.\\n\\n**Verdict: no issue.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### `resolveLatestCheckpoint()` — \\\"get latest checkpoint\\\" logic\\n\\n**The new function (resume.go:188-201):**\\n\\n```go\\nfunc resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo *git.Repository, checkpointIDs []id.CheckpointID) (id.CheckpointID, error) {\\n    metadataTree, err := getMetadataTree(repo)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, err\\n    }\\n    sorted := collectCheckpointsByAge(metadataTree, checkpointIDs)\\n    if len(sorted) == 0 {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")\\n    }\\n    return sorted[len(sorted)-1].CheckpointID, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Does similar \\\"get the latest\\\" logic exist elsewhere?** Searching the codebase for `GetMetadataBranchTree` usage at:\\n\\n- `strategy/session.go:187` — reads a single checkpoint tree, does not sort or compare multiple, no overlap.\\n- `strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go:163` — best-effort read for session prompts, no sorting, no overlap.\\n- `explain.go:927` — iterates commits and reads their checkpoint metadata one at a time via `ReadCheckpointMetadata`, does not compare `CreatedAt` across a set of IDs, no overlap.\\n\\nNo existing \\\"sort by CreatedAt and return last\\\" pattern exists elsewhere in the codebase. `collectCheckpointsByAge` itself was already present before this diff. `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a thin wrapper that adds the `getMetadataTree` step and the tail-element extraction — it is not duplicating any other utility.\\n\\n**Verdict: no issue.**\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:212]** `getMetadataTree` calls `FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background())` instead of threading through the `ctx` passed to its call sites. This drops any cancellation or deadline set by the caller (for example, a CLI timeout). The function signature only takes `*git.Repository`, so `ctx` is unavailable inside it without a signature change.\\n\\nThere are two practical approaches:\\n\\nOption A — add `ctx` parameter:\\n```go\\nfunc getMetadataTree(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n```\\nand pass `ctx` through from `resolveLatestCheckpoint`, which would in turn receive it from `resumeFromCurrentBranch`. This is the cleanest fix.\\n\\nOption B — leave `context.Background()` and add a comment explaining the limitation. Acceptable only if the fetch is intentionally fire-and-forget, but given that the rest of `resume.go` passes `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch` (line 417), this is inconsistent.\\n\\nThe deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` passed the real `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch`. This is a regression introduced by the refactor. Notably, this exact issue does not appear in `checkRemoteMetadata` (line 417) which correctly receives `ctx` and passes it through.\\n\\n**Fix:** Add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to `getMetadataTree` and update the two call sites (`resolveLatestCheckpoint` and any direct callers).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:196]** `resolveLatestCheckpoint` calls `getMetadataTree` which may perform a network fetch. At the call site (resume.go:160), if `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails, the fallback is `result.checkpointIDs[len-1]` (the last trailer), which is the same checkpoint that `resumeFromCurrentBranch` would have used for the single-checkpoint path anyway. This means the fetch in `getMetadataTree` is speculative: it is attempted even in contexts where a simpler fallback is acceptable. This is not a bug, but a `logging.Debug` call on the `resolveLatestCheckpoint` error path (currently silently ignored at line 162) would improve diagnosability when the fetch fails.\\n\\n**[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:163]** The fallback comment says \\\"use last trailer\\\" — in practice this means the most recently added trailer, which by the squash-merge ordering tested in the integration test corresponds to the most recently created checkpoint. This happens to be correct, but it is order-dependent on how `git` serialises trailers during squash merge. A comment linking to the ordering assumption (or the test that validates it) would make the fallback easier to audit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- Extracting `getMetadataTree()` correctly eliminates the duplication of the three-step fallback pattern that previously existed inline in `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`. The pre-diff code had that logic in one place; the post-diff code also has it in one place, just named.\\n- `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a clean, single-responsibility wrapper. The two-call test in `resume_test.go` (reverse-order and chronological-order) directly validates the invariant.\\n- Removing `deduplicateSessions` and `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` reduces the file by ~100 lines without losing correctness — the squash-merge case is now handled by returning the single latest checkpoint rather than restoring all of them, which is a simpler and more predictable user experience.\\n- The integration test update (`TestResume_SquashMergeMultipleCheckpoints`) correctly reflects the new behaviour: it now asserts on the `\\\"older checkpoints skipped\\\"` message and session2 ID rather than \\\"Restored 2 sessions\\\" and both session IDs.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\nOne issue must be addressed before merge:\\n\\n- **[resume.go:212]** `context.Background()` in `getMetadataTree` is a regression from the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`, which passed the real `ctx`. Add `ctx context.Context` to `getMetadataTree`'s signature.\\n\\nNo code-reuse problems were found. `getMetadataTree` is a correct extraction of logic that was previously duplicated between the call sites. `resolveLatestCheckpoint` does not duplicate any existing utility.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address: ~15 minutes** (signature change + two call sites).\",\"new_string\":\"# Review 04\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-04\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: APPROVE\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis review covers the single commit `d90158f2` (\\\"use only the latest checkpoint for entire resume on squashed commits\\\"), which modifies:\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/resume.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/resume_test.go`\\n- `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/resume_test.go`\\n\\nThe change replaces the multi-session restore path (`resumeMultipleCheckpoints`) with a single-session path that resolves the latest checkpoint by `CreatedAt` timestamp.\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\nThe issues from review-03 are unrelated to this diff (they concern `UpdateCommitted` redaction, `KNOWN_LIMITATIONS.md`, and uncommitted strategy changes). This review focuses exclusively on the code quality of the squash-merge checkpoint resolution change.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n1. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:156-168]** The initial assignment `checkpointID := result.checkpointIDs[0]` is a dead write when `len(result.checkpointIDs) > 1`. The value assigned on line 156 is unconditionally overwritten on line 168 (`checkpointID = latest`). This makes a reader wonder whether `checkpointIDs[0]` has any semantic significance in the multi-checkpoint case, and invites doubt about whether `[0]` or `[len-1]` is the right element. A cleaner structure removes the ambiguity entirely:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   var checkpointID id.CheckpointID\\n   if len(result.checkpointIDs) == 1 {\\n       checkpointID = result.checkpointIDs[0]\\n   } else {\\n       // Multiple checkpoints (squash merge): resolve latest and resume from it\\n       latest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\n       if err != nil {\\n           // Fallback: use last trailer\\n           latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n       }\\n       skipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit in this branch, resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs), skipped)\\n       checkpointID = latest\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n   This makes both branches explicit: `[0]` for the single case, `latest` for the multi case. No dead write, no misleading initial value.\\n\\n2. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:212]** `getMetadataTree` calls `FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background())` instead of threading through the caller's context. The function signature only accepts `*git.Repository`, so cancellation and deadlines from the parent context are silently ignored during the fetch step. This is a regression from the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints`, which passed the real `ctx` to `FetchMetadataBranch`. Every other call to `FetchMetadataBranch` in `resume.go` (line 417) uses the real context.\\n\\n   Fix: add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to both `getMetadataTree` and `resolveLatestCheckpoint`, and propagate from `resumeFromCurrentBranch`.\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n1. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:161-163]** The fallback uses `result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]` (last trailer) when metadata cannot be read. The squash-merge integration test documents that trailers appear in chronological order (oldest first), which would make `[len-1]` the most recent. However, the ordering is a property of how `git` serialises the squash commit message and is not guaranteed by any specification. A short comment on the fallback line noting this assumption would help future readers:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   // Fallback: use last trailer. Trailer order during squash merge is chronological\\n   // (oldest first), so the last trailer is typically the most recent checkpoint.\\n   latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:164-167]** The informational message (\\\"resuming from the latest\\\") is printed regardless of whether `resolveLatestCheckpoint` succeeded or fell back. In the fallback case the selection is a heuristic (last trailer), not a verified latest. Splitting the message by outcome would be more accurate:\\n\\n   ```go\\n   if err != nil {\\n       latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit, could not determine order (resuming from last)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs))\\n   } else {\\n       skipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\n       fmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints on the latest commit in this branch, resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\",\\n           len(result.checkpointIDs), skipped)\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume.go:160-162]** When `resolveLatestCheckpoint` fails silently at the call site, the error is discarded without any log entry. Adding a `logging.Debug` call would help with diagnosing future reports of \\\"resumed wrong session\\\":\\n\\n   ```go\\n   latest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\n   if err != nil {\\n       logging.Debug(ctx, \\\"could not resolve latest checkpoint, using last trailer\\\",\\n           slog.String(\\\"error\\\", err.Error()),\\n       )\\n       latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n   }\\n   ```\\n\\n4. **[cmd/entire/cli/resume_test.go:443-481]** `TestResolveLatestCheckpoint` does not test the error path where none of the provided checkpoint IDs exist in the metadata tree. A test calling `resolveLatestCheckpoint` with IDs that have no metadata entries would verify that `errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")` propagates correctly and that callers get a usable signal to fall back on.\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- Removing `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` and `deduplicateSessions` is a clear simplification. The old path was ~80 lines to restore all sessions and deduplicate by `SessionID`. The new path is ~10 lines to pick the single latest checkpoint. The feature change (resume only the most recent session, not all) is a legitimate product decision and the code correctly implements it.\\n\\n- `getMetadataTree` cleanly encapsulates the three-step fallback (local branch first, then fetch, then remote tree directly). Step ordering is correct: cheapest operation first, network calls only as needed. The comments on each step are clear and accurate.\\n\\n- `collectCheckpointsByAge` is unchanged and correct. Sorting ascending by `CreatedAt` and returning the tail element is a correct, readable implementation of \\\"find the latest.\\\"\\n\\n- `resolveLatestCheckpoint` is a thin, single-responsibility wrapper. The doc comment explains the three-step fallback strategy without overstating what the function does.\\n\\n- The integration test update (`TestResume_SquashMergeMultipleCheckpoints`) correctly narrows the assertion: from \\\"Restored 2 sessions\\\" and both session IDs, to \\\"older checkpoints skipped\\\" and only `session2.ID`. The test accurately reflects the new single-session contract.\\n\\n- `TestResolveLatestCheckpoint` tests both orderings of the input slice (reverse-chronological and chronological), which is the exact scenario that motivated this change. This directly validates the core invariant.\\n\\n- Deleting `TestDeduplicateSessions` alongside `deduplicateSessions` is correct housekeeping. Tests for deleted code should not linger.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\nThe change is a clean simplification with correct logic and appropriate test updates. Two issues are worth addressing before merge:\\n\\n1. **Important [resume.go:156]** — the dead initial write of `checkpointID` creates reader confusion; restructure to make single vs. multi-checkpoint paths distinct branches.\\n2. **Important [resume.go:212]** — `context.Background()` in `getMetadataTree` drops the caller's context, breaking cancellation propagation; this is a regression from the deleted code.\\n\\nThe suggestions are low-priority polish: a comment on the fallback ordering assumption, distinct messages for the success vs. fallback paths, a debug log on the silent error discard, and an error-path unit test for `resolveLatestCheckpoint`.\\n\\n**Overall verdict: APPROVE** — the logic is correct and the simplification is a net improvement. The two Important items improve clarity and correctness but are not blockers for correctness of the feature itself.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback: ~30 minutes**\\n- Restructure `checkpointID` assignment: ~10 minutes\\n- Add `ctx` parameter to `getMetadataTree` and `resolveLatestCheckpoint`: ~10 minutes\\n- Optional message accuracy, debug logging, error-path test: ~10 minutes\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2911,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":63506,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":2911},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYhtyuY6mYh3sS4uzYVok\",\"uuid\":\"2ce8d15e-3674-494d-9705-cc1232a5348d\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\"type\":\"agent_progress\",\"prompt\":\"\",\"agentId\":\"a89c0a9858f95dd0e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01Cefnh1vBkZAEVuFxXh1GyF\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01TaBUrhmiHzHp5MBwgav4pT\",\"uuid\":\"0ed63f3c-d569-41c3-a700-7038e6996c40\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:41:01.183Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"0ed63f3c-d569-41c3-a700-7038e6996c40\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01LLW8yUCHFB4tatEE5eWksE\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"The file /Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/single-commit-per-checkpoint/review-04.md has been upd