ed by this commit.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Critical (Must Fix)\\n\\n**1. [resume.go:212] `FetchMetadataBranch` called with `context.Background()` — drops\\ncancellation and timeout from the caller**\\n\\n```go\\nif fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background()); fetchErr == nil {\\n```\\n\\n`FetchMetadataBranch` wraps the fetch in its own 2-minute timeout (`git_operations.go`\\nline 365), so the operation is not truly unbounded. However, using `context.Background()`\\ninstead of the caller-provided `ctx` means that if the user sends SIGINT / Ctrl-C while\\nthe CLI is running, the fetch will not be cancelled. The user will have to wait up to 2\\nminutes for the timeout to fire before the process exits.\\n\\nEvery other call to `FetchMetadataBranch` in the file (lines 97 and 417) correctly\\nthreads `ctx` through. This one is inconsistent because `getMetadataTree` does not\\nreceive a `ctx` parameter.\\n\\nThe fix is to add `ctx context.Context` as the first parameter to both `getMetadataTree`\\nand `resolveLatestCheckpoint`:\\n\\n```go\\n// Before\\nfunc getMetadataTree(repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n    ...\\n    if fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(context.Background()); fetchErr == nil {\\n\\n// After\\nfunc getMetadataTree(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository) (*object.Tree, error) {\\n    ...\\n    if fetchErr := FetchMetadataBranch(ctx); fetchErr == nil {\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Important (Should Fix)\\n\\n**2. [resume.go:191-200 vs 172-185] `GetMetadataBranchTree` is called twice in the\\nmulti-checkpoint path — redundant reference resolution**\\n\\nThe call sequence when `len(result.checkpointIDs) > 1`:\\n\\n```\\nresumeFromCurrentBranch\\n  └── resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, ...)\\n        └── getMetadataTree(repo)\\n              └── strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)   ← reference + commit + tree: call #1\\n\\n  // resolveLatestCheckpoint returns only checkpointID, discards the tree\\n\\n  └── strategy.GetMetadataBranchTree(repo)               ← reference + commit + tree: call #2\\n  └── strategy.ReadCheckpointMetadata(metadataTree, ...)\\n```\\n\\n`GetMetadataBranchTree` resolves a branch reference via `repo.Reference()`, reads the\\ncommit object via `repo.CommitObject()`, and resolves the tree — three go-git calls per\\ninvocation. In the local-cache case these are cheap filesystem reads, but they are not\\nfree and are entirely redundant here.\\n\\nIn the **remote-fetch path** the redundancy is more severe: when the local branch is\\nabsent, `getMetadataTree` may call `FetchMetadataBranch` and re-resolve the tree (two\\ncalls inside `getMetadataTree`), after which `resumeFromCurrentBranch` makes a third\\ncall. Worse, if the third fallback path inside `getMetadataTree` is used\\n(`GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree`), the sorting works but then `resumeFromCurrentBranch`'s\\n`GetMetadataBranchTree` fails (local still absent), falls into `checkRemoteMetadata`,\\nwhich calls `GetRemoteMetadataBranchTree` a fourth time and `ReadCheckpointMetadata`\\nagain for the same checkpoint.\\n\\nThe fix is to return the resolved tree alongside the checkpoint ID from\\n`resolveLatestCheckpoint` so the caller can reuse it:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc resolveLatestCheckpoint(ctx context.Context, repo *git.Repository, ids []id.CheckpointID) (id.CheckpointID, *object.Tree, error) {\\n    tree, err := getMetadataTree(ctx, repo)\\n    if err != nil {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, nil, err\\n    }\\n    sorted := collectCheckpointsByAge(tree, ids)\\n    if len(sorted) == 0 {\\n        return id.EmptyCheckpointID, nil, errors.New(\\\"no checkpoint metadata found\\\")\\n    }\\n    return sorted[len(sorted)-1].CheckpointID, tree, nil\\n}\\n```\\n\\n`resumeFromCurrentBranch` then uses the returned tree directly for the `ReadCheckpointMetadata`\\ncall, skipping the second `GetMetadataBranchTree` invocation.\\n\\n**3. [resume.go:231-243] `collectCheckpointsByAge` reads full per-session metadata for\\nevery checkpoint just to compare timestamps — unnecessarily broad I/O**\\n\\n`ReadCheckpointMetadata` does the following for each checkpoint (new format path,\\n`common.go:377-414`):\\n\\n1. Reads and JSON-parses the root `metadata.json` (a `CheckpointSummary`) — one file read\\n2. Loops over every session path in `summary.Sessions`, reads and JSON-parses each\\n   per-session `metadata.json` — S additional file reads per checkpoint\\n\\nThis is O(N * S) file reads to compare N timestamps, where S is the session count per\\ncheckpoint. All fields except `CreatedAt` and `CheckpointID` are discarded by\\n`collectCheckpointsByAge`.\\n\\nSince `CreatedAt` comes from the first session's `metadata.json` (line 401 of\\n`ReadCheckpointMetadata`: \\\"Use first session for ... CreatedAt\\\"), a lighter helper could\\nstop after reading the first session file. The remaining S-1 session files are wasted\\nreads for the timestamp-comparison purpose.\\n\\nIn practice squash commits accumulate only a handful of trailers (2–5), so this is not a\\nscalability crisis. But for a `resume` command that a user runs interactively, every\\navoidable file read adds latency. A targeted fix:\\n\\n```go\\n// readCheckpointTimestamp reads only enough metadata to get CreatedAt.\\n// For the new format, reads root metadata.json then only the first session metadata.json.\\nfunc readCheckpointTimestamp(tree *object.Tree, checkpointPath string) (time.Time, error) {\\n    // ... read CheckpointSummary, then read only sessions[0].Metadata\\n}\\n```\\n\\nUse this in `collectCheckpointsByAge` instead of the full `ReadCheckpointMetadata`. Once\\nthe winning checkpoint is determined, do the full read once.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Suggestions (Consider)\\n\\n**4. [resume.go:163] Fallback to last trailer should be documented**\\n\\n```go\\nif err != nil {\\n    // Fallback: use last trailer\\n    latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe assumption that \\\"last trailer = latest checkpoint\\\" is reasonable (git commit messages\\npreserve insertion order) but is not self-evident to a future reader. The existing comment\\nis minimal. A slightly expanded comment would help:\\n\\n```go\\n// Fallback: trailers appear in insertion order; the last one was\\n// appended most recently so it is the best proxy for \\\"latest\\\".\\nlatest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n```\\n\\n**5. [resume.go:163-168] The \\\"older checkpoints skipped\\\" message prints even when\\n`resolveLatestCheckpoint` failed and the fallback was used**\\n\\n```go\\nlatest, err := resolveLatestCheckpoint(repo, result.checkpointIDs)\\nif err != nil {\\n    latest = result.checkpointIDs[len(result.checkpointIDs)-1]\\n}\\nskipped := len(result.checkpointIDs) - 1\\nfmt.Fprintf(os.Stderr, \\\"Found %d checkpoints ... resuming from the latest (%d older checkpoints skipped)\\\\n\\\", ...)\\n```\\n\\nThe phrase \\\"resuming from the latest\\\" implies metadata was consulted to determine\\nrecency. When the error path fires, the selection is by trailer order, not by timestamp.\\nConsider branching the message or adding a parenthetical \\\"(by trailer order, metadata\\nunavailable)\\\" so the user is not misled when debugging.\\n\\n**6. [resume.go] The debug logging path from the deleted `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` is\\ngone**\\n\\nThe old function logged `\\\"metadata branch not available locally, trying remote\\\"` when\\nfalling back to fetch. `getMetadataTree` is silent — it just tries each path and returns.\\nIf the fetch silently fails (e.g., no origin remote configured), the only signal is the\\neventual `resolveLatestCheckpoint` error, which is itself swallowed by the fallback. A\\nsingle `logging.Debug` inside `getMetadataTree` when fetch is attempted would preserve\\ndiagnosability.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Praise\\n\\n- The core behaviour change is correct and the UX is better. Restoring all sessions from\\n  a squash commit is surprising; selecting the latest and noting what was skipped is the\\n  right default.\\n\\n- Removing `resumeMultipleCheckpoints` (60 lines) and `deduplicateSessions` (35 lines)\\n  in exchange for `resolveLatestCheckpoint` (10 lines) + `getMetadataTree` (20 lines) is\\n  a meaningful reduction in complexity for a change in behaviour that is arguably more\\n  correct.\\n\\n- `collectCheckpointsByAge` is correctly reused rather than duplicated. The sort-ascending\\n  / return-last pattern is clear and correct.\\n\\n- The integration test update (`resume_test.go`) accurately captures the new contract:\\n  single session restored, skipped-count message present, the older session ID absent.\\n\\n- The fallback to trailer-order when metadata is unavailable is a sound degradation\\n  strategy — the command still completes rather than erroring out.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n**Overall assessment: REQUEST CHANGES**\\n\\nTwo issues warrant fixing before merge:\\n\\n1. **`context.Background()` in `getMetadataTree`** prevents signal cancellation. The fix\\n   is straightforward: add `ctx` as a parameter and thread it through.\\n\\n2. **Double (and in some paths, triple+) metadata tree resolution.** `resolveLatestCheckpoint`\\n   fetches the tree, discards it, then `resumeFromCurrentBranch` fetches it again. The\\n   tree should be returned from `resolveLatestCheckpoint` and reused.\\n\\nOne issue is worth addressing but not a blocker:\\n\\n3. **`collectCheckpointsByAge` reads all per-session metadata files** when only\\n   `CreatedAt` from the first session is needed. A lightweight timestamp-only read would\\n   halve or better the I/O per checkpoint.\\n\\n**Estimated effort: ~45 minutes**\\n- Context threading + tree reuse (items 1 + 2): ~25 minutes\\n- Timestamp-only read helper (item 3): ~15 minutes\\n- Comment and log additions (items 4-6): ~5 minutes\\nREVIEW_EOF\",\"description\":\"Write review-04.md to the single-commit-per-checkpoint requirements folder\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_re