858\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01TnECKHRzg4WJyDncfDwkfk\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The two formats are actually quite different. Here's the key insight:\\n\\n**GitHub squash merge** — individual commit messages are concatenated into the body. Each original commit had its own `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer, so they appear scattered throughout:\\n```\\nFeature branch (#1)\\n\\n* Create hello script\\n\\nEntire-Checkpoint: aaa111bbb222\\n\\n* Create goodbye script\\n\\nEntire-Checkpoint: ccc333ddd444\\n```\\n\\n**Git CLI squash merge** (`git merge --squash && git commit`) — git prepopulates the commit message similarly, but the `prepare-commit-msg` hook fires with `source=\\\"squash\\\"`. We currently skip it.\\n\\nThe detection is straightforward: from the parser's perspective, both produce a commit with multiple `Entire-Checkpoint` lines — `ParseAllCheckpoints` already handles both identically via regex. The trailer format is the same regardless of source.\\n\\nThe real difference is **when** we can act:\\n\\n- **GitHub squash**: We can only act at **resume time** (post-hoc), which is what we just implemented. The merge happens on GitHub's servers — no hooks fire locally.\\n- **Git CLI squash**: We *could* act at **commit time** via the `prepare-commit-msg` hook (currently skipped for `source=\\\"squash\\\"`). We could detect the multiple trailers in the squash message, resolve the latest, and rewrite the message to keep only that one trailer.\\n\\nBut I'm not sure that's worth doing. Here's why:\\n\\n1. The resume-time resolution already handles both formats correctly\\n2. Stripping old trailers at commit time loses information — if someone wants to trace which checkpoints were part of a squash, the trailers are the audit trail\\n3. It adds complexity to the hook for a scenario that's already handled\\n4. Local `git merge --squash` is indeed less common than GitHub squash merges\\n\\nThe one scenario where commit-time handling could help: someone does `git log` and sees multiple trailers and wonders \\\"which one is current?\\\" But that's a cosmetic concern, not a functional one.\\n\\nWant me to explore the hook approach further, or does the current resume-time resolution feel sufficient for both formats?\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":4786,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":119351,\"output_tokens\":500,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4786,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYhui2VE6hazKyegD7aqP\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"0933f3c5-16a7-4cf3-b92e-2c476e09f74b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:49:25.334Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"0933f3c5-16a7-4cf3-b92e-2c476e09f74b\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"cf32cb7d-e69d-4fde-838f-a801d52d6b92\",\"version\":\"2.1.66\",\"gitBranch\":\"soph/latest-squash-resume\",\"slug\":\"purrfect-toasting-stream\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"87c1f574-9731-407d-bf0f-0763db67f134\",\"toolUseID\":\"87c1f574-9731-407d-bf0f-0763db67f134\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-04T10:49:25.423Z\",\"uuid\":\"9e78468a-f642-4ab4-a24f-0ebb9ddf4454\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9e78468a-f642-4ab4-a24f-0ebb9ddf4454\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":